{"id":"1609.06235","submitter":"Trevor Richards","authors":"Trevor Richards","title":"Boundary convergence and path divergence sets for bounded analytic\n  functions in the disk","comments":"6 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CV","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $f:\\mathbb{D}\\to\\mathbb{C}$ be a bounded analytic function. A set\n$K\\subset\\mathbb{D}$ which contains the point $1$ in its boundary is called a\nconvergence set for $f$ at $1$ if $f(z)$ converges to some value $\\zeta$ as\n$z\\to1$ with $z\\in K$. $K$ is called a path divergence set for $f$ at $1$ if\n$f$ diverges along every path $\\gamma$ which lies in $K$ and approaches $1$. In\nthis article, we show that for a path $\\gamma$ through the unit disk from $-1$\nto $1$, if $f$ fails to converge along $\\gamma$, then either the region above\n$\\gamma$ or the region below $\\gamma$ is a path divergence set for $f$. On the\nother hand, if $\\gamma_1$ and $\\gamma_2$ are two such paths, and $f$ converges\nalong both $\\gamma_1$ and $\\gamma_2$, then the region between $\\gamma_1$ and\n$\\gamma_2$ is a convergence set for $f$. This latter fact is immediate when\n$\\gamma_1$ and $\\gamma_2$ do not intersect except at their end-points, but\nbecomes non-trivial when $\\gamma_1$ and $\\gamma_2$ are highly intersecting. We\nconclude the paper with an examination of the convergence sets for the function\n$e^{\\frac{z+1}{z-1}}$ at $1$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 20 Sep 2016 16:09:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 28 Sep 2016 18:49:08 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 19 Jun 2019 17:22:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-06-20"}
